  "prompt_text": "Explain the concept of Big-O notation. Rank the following: O(n!), O(2^n), O(n^2), O(n log n), O(n), O(log n), O(1).",
  "response_text": "Big-O notation is a mathematical notation used to describe the complexity of an algorithm in terms of time or space required as the input size grows. It provides an upper bound on the growth rate of the algorithm's resource usage, focusing on the worst-case scenario and ignoring constant factors and lower-order terms.\n\nTo rank the given Big-O complexities from highest to lowest growth rates as the input size \\(n\\) increases:\n\n1. **O(n!)** - Factorial growth, which increases extremely rapidly. For example, \\(5! = 120\\), \\(10! = 3,628,800\\).\n2. **O(2^n)** - Exponential growth, where the function doubles for every increment in \\(n\\). This is faster than factorial growth for large \\(n\\).\n3. **O(n^2)** - Quadratic growth, which means the function grows quadratically with respect to \\(n\\). Common in nested loops.\n4. **O(n log n)** - Growth that is proportional to \\(n\\) times the logarithm of \\(n\\). Often seen in efficient sorting algorithms like merge sort.\n5. **O(n)** - Linear growth, where the function grows directly proportional to \\(n\\). Simple linear scans over data.\n6. **O(log n)** - Logarithmic growth, where the function grows in proportion to the logarithm of \\(n\\). Common in binary search algorithms.\n7. **O(1)** - Constant time, where the function's execution time does not depend on the size of \\(n\\). Operations that take the same amount of time regardless of input size.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 10\nP (Pattern Recognition): 9\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 8\nQ (Query Interpretation): 10\nC (Contextual Awareness): 9\nY (Affective Modeling): 8\nF (Flexibility): 8\nD (Depth of Processing): 9\n---END RATINGS---",
